{{Infobox software | screenshot = abcathome.png | caption = ABC@Home project logo | author = | developer = [[University of Leiden]] | released = | latest release version = 2.10 | latest release date = {{start date and age|2010|08|22}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcathome.com/apps.php |title=Applications |publisher=ABC@Home |accessdate=2010-10-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917032533/http://abcathome.com/apps.php |archivedate=17 September 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> | latest preview version = | latest preview date = | operating system = | platform = [[Cross-platform]] | language = English | genre = [[Volunteer computing]] | license = Proprietary | website = [https://www.math.leidenuniv.nl/~desmit/abc/index.php?set=1 ABC@Home] }}
'''ABC@Home''' was an educational and non-profit [[computer network|network computing]] project finding abc-triples related to the [[abc conjecture]] in number theory.
Using the [[Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing]] (BOINC) [[distributed computing]] platform. In March 2011, there were more than 7,300 active participants from 114 countries with a total [[BOINC Credit System|BOINC credit]] of more than 2.9 billion, reporting about 10 [[FLOPS|teraflops]] (10 trillion operations per second) of processing power.<ref>{{citation |url=http://boincstats.com/stats/project_graph.php?pr=abc_main |title=Detailed user, host, team and country statistics with graphs for BOINC |accessdate=2011-03-11 |work=boincstats.com |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120150315/http://boincstats.com/stats/project_graph.php?pr=abc_main |archivedate=2010-11-20 |df= }}</ref>
In 2011, the project met its goal of finding all abc-triples of at most 18 digits. By 2015, the project had found 23.8 million triples in total, and ceased operations soon after.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.math.leidenuniv.nl/~desmit/abc/index.php?set=1 |title=ABC Triples |last=de Smit |first=Bart |accessdate=2017-03-09}}</ref>
