In English and related languages, several terms involving the words "great" or "gross" (possibly, from {{lang-fr|[[wikt:grosse|grosse]]}} thick) relate to numbers involving multiples of exponents of [[12 (number)|twelve]] ([[dozen]]): *A '''gross''' refers to a group of [[144 (number)|144]] items (a dozen dozen or a square dozen, 12<sup>2</sup>).<ref name="wm"/><ref name="ubm"/> *A '''great gross''' refers to a group of [[1728 (number)|1728]] items (a dozen gross or a cubic dozen, 12<sup>3</sup>).<ref name="wm">{{citation|title=The Words of Mathematics: An Etymological Dictionary of Mathematical Terms Used in English|first=Steven|last=Schwartzman|publisher=[[Mathematical Association of America]]|year=1996|isbn=9780883855119|pages=100–101|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SRw4PevE4zUC&pg=PA10}}.</ref><ref name="ubm">{{citation|title=The Universal Book of Mathematics: From Abracadabra to Zeno's Paradoxes|first=David|last=Darling|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2004|isbn=9780471270478|page=140|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nnpChqstvg0C&pg=PA140}}.</ref> *A '''small gross'''<ref>{{citation|title=The New Century Book of Facts: A Handbook of Ready Reference|first=Carroll Davidson|last=Wright|publisher=King-Richardson Company|year=1910|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JnBMAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA462|page=462}}.</ref> or a '''great hundred'''<ref>{{citation|title=The Penguin Dictionary of Curious and Interesting Numbers|first=David|last=Wells|edition=3rd|publisher=Penguin|year=1997|isbn=9780140261493|page=66|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kQRPkTkk_VIC&pg=PA66}}.</ref> refers to a group of [[120 (number)|120]] items (ten dozen, 10×12</sup>). Early 15c., from Old French grosse douzaine "large dozen." <ref>https://www.etymonline.com/word/gross</ref>
A gross may be abbreviated as "gr" or "gro".
The continued use of these numbers in measurement and counting represents a continuation of the tradition of the [[duodecimal]] number system in everyday life<ref>{{citation|title=Mathematics: From the Birth of Numbers|first=Jan|last=Gullberg|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=1997|isbn=9780393040029}}.</ref> and has encouraged groups such as the Dozenal Society of America to advocate for a wider use of such a numbering system in place of [[decimal]].<ref>{{citation|title=Mathematical Cranks|first=Underwood|last=Dudley|authorlink=Underwood Dudley|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1996|isbn=9780883855072|page=22|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HqeoWPsIH6EC&pg=PA23&lpg=PA22}}.</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Dozenalists of the world unite! Rise up against the tyranny of ten!|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2012-12-12|first=Alex|last=Bellos|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/alexs-adventures-in-numberland/2012/dec/12/dozenalists-world-unite-tyranny-ten}}.</ref>
